training_organizations.name: Missouri Children’s Division – Professional Development & Training
training_organizations.description: The Missouri Children’s Division (within the Department of Social Services) runs a Professional Development and Training unit that educates child welfare staff. New caseworkers go through a competency-based training program including simulation labs for court and home visits. Ongoing training is provided via regional training staff and online modules, covering Missouri’s practice model and initiatives.

training_organizations.name: Great Circle
training_organizations.description: A Missouri nonprofit that provides a continuum of behavioral health services for children and families, including those in the child welfare system. Great Circle contracts with the state to offer specialized foster care (for children with higher therapeutic needs) and residential treatment programs. They also provide parenting support and crisis services. Missouri’s Children’s Division utilizes Great Circle’s programs for children who need intensive services or placements that the state cannot directly provide.

training_organizations.name: Cornerstones of Care (Missouri)
training_organizations.description: A nonprofit agency active in Missouri (and Kansas) that partners with the state on child welfare services. Cornerstones of Care holds contracts to supervise some foster homes and deliver services like family therapy and parent education under Missouri’s “purchase of service” system:contentReference[oaicite:25]{index=25}. In pilot programs (e.g., in the Kansas City region), Cornerstones of Care has managed foster care cases to help the state evaluate outcomes of partial privatization:contentReference[oaicite:26]{index=26}.

training_organizations.name: FosterAdopt Connect
training_organizations.description: A nonprofit organization serving Missouri (based in the Kansas City area) that supports foster and adoptive families. FosterAdopt Connect runs programs such as foster parent mentoring, support for kinship caregivers, and behavioral interventions for foster youth. The Children’s Division contracts with organizations like this to assist with foster parent retention and to provide wraparound services, improving stability for children in care.
